# NestJS Conventions

## Server App Structure

```
apps/<name>-server/
  package.json                   → extends shared deps pattern
  tsconfig.json                  → extends tsconfig.nest.json
  nest-cli.json                  → SWC builder + Swagger plugin
  vitest.config.ts               → test config (globals: true, include src/**/*.test.ts)
  src/
    main.ts                      → bootstrap: loadMonorepoEnv + NestFactory + ValidationPipe + setupSwagger + listen
    app.module.ts                → imports HealthModule, LlmModule.register([...]), feature modules
    tokens.ts                    → injection token constants (NEVER in app.module.ts)
    prompts/
      index.ts                   → re-exports all prompt constants
      <name>.ts                  → each system prompt as named export constant
    modules/
      <feature>/
        <feature>.module.ts
        <feature>.controller.ts
        <feature>.controller.test.ts  ← TEST OBLIGATORIO
        <feature>.service.ts
        <feature>.service.test.ts     ← TEST OBLIGATORIO
        dto/                     → (app-specific DTOs only)
```

## Bootstrap Pattern — main.ts

Every NestJS server MUST follow this exact bootstrap sequence:

```typescript
import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core'
import { ValidationPipe } from '@nestjs/common'
import { loadMonorepoEnv, setupSwagger } from '@primer-guidy/nest-shared'
import { AppModule } from './app.module'

const DEFAULT_PORT = 3010

loadMonorepoEnv(__dirname)

async function bootstrap() {
  const app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule)
  app.useGlobalPipes(new ValidationPipe({ whitelist: true, transform: true }))

  setupSwagger(app, {
    title: 'My API',
    description: 'API description',
    version: '1.0',
  })

  const port = process.env['PORT'] ?? DEFAULT_PORT
  await app.listen(port)
}

void bootstrap()
```

- `loadMonorepoEnv(__dirname)` MUST be called BEFORE `NestFactory.create()` — it loads `.env.local` then `.env` from monorepo root
- `setupSwagger` provides automatic API docs at `/docs`
- Public-facing servers SHOULD call `app.enableCors()` after `NestFactory.create()`

## Injection Tokens — src/tokens.ts

Injection tokens MUST live in a dedicated `src/tokens.ts` file, NEVER in `app.module.ts`. This prevents circular dependencies during module initialization.

```typescript
// src/tokens.ts
export const LLM_PROVIDER = 'ILlmProvider'
```

```typescript
// src/modules/generation/generation.service.ts
import { LLM_PROVIDER } from '../../tokens'

@Injectable()
export class GenerationService {
  constructor(@Inject(LLM_PROVIDER) private readonly llm: ILlmProvider) {}
}
```

## System Prompts — src/prompts/

System prompt strings MUST live in `src/prompts/` with one file per prompt and an `index.ts` barrel:

```
src/prompts/
  index.ts                → export { GUARD_SYSTEM_PROMPT } from './guard'
  guard.ts                → export const GUARD_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `...`
  curation.ts             → export const CURATION_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `...`
```

NEVER define system prompts inline in service files. The `prompts/` folder makes them easy to find, iterate on, and tune.

## Shared Modules — `@primer-guidy/nest-shared`

Before creating any module, check if `@primer-guidy/nest-shared` already provides it:

| Module | Usage |
|--------|-------|
| `HealthModule` | Import directly — provides `GET /health` |
| `LlmModule.register([...])` | Configure LLM providers with token + env var mappings |
| `ApiKeyGuard` | Apply via `@UseGuards(ApiKeyGuard)` for server-to-server auth |
| `PromptContextDto` | Use as `@Body()` parameter for prompt + context endpoints |
| `GenerationResponseDto` | Return type for LLM generation responses |
| `setupSwagger(app, config)` | Swagger UI at `/docs` with API key security scheme |
| `loadMonorepoEnv(appDir)` | Loads `.env.local` then `.env` from monorepo root |

```typescript
// app.module.ts — typical server setup
import { HealthModule, LlmModule } from '@primer-guidy/nest-shared'
import { LLM_PROVIDER } from './tokens'

@Module({
  imports: [
    HealthModule,
    LlmModule.register([
      { token: LLM_PROVIDER, modelEnv: 'ANTHROPIC_MODEL', defaultModel: 'claude-sonnet-4-6' },
    ]),
    FeatureModule,
  ],
})
export class AppModule {}
```

## Shared Configs

ALL NestJS servers MUST use the shared configs:

| Config | Path | What it provides |
|--------|------|-----------------|
| `tsconfig.nest.json` | `../../tsconfig.nest.json` | CommonJS, node resolution, decorators, strict mode, `types: ["node"]` |
| Root `eslint.config.mjs` | Monorepo root | NestJS-specific overrides for modules and DI files |
| `nest-cli.json` | Per server (identical) | SWC builder + Swagger plugin |

Server `tsconfig.json` MUST extend `tsconfig.nest.json` and add `outDir` + decorator flags:

```json
{
  "extends": "../../tsconfig.nest.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "outDir": "dist",
    "experimentalDecorators": true,
    "emitDecoratorMetadata": true
  },
  "include": ["src/**/*"],
  "exclude": ["node_modules", "dist", "**/*.test.ts"]
}
```

ESLint NestJS overrides live in the ROOT `eslint.config.mjs` — it scopes rules to NestJS file patterns for IDE linting. Each server also has its own minimal `eslint.config.mjs` that extends the shared `nestServer` preset — this is required by the Nx CLI for per-project `nx lint` targets. Both configs are needed; do NOT flag per-server ESLint configs as violations during audits.

## Single Responsibility per Service

Each service handles ONE domain concern. Never mix responsibilities.

```typescript
// BAD — mixed concerns
@Injectable()
class UserService {
  createUser() { /* ... */ }
  sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ }
  generateReport() { /* ... */ }
}

// GOOD — separated
@Injectable()
class UserService { createUser() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class NotificationService { sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class ReportService { generateReport() { /* ... */ } }
```

## Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Responsibility |
|-------|---------------|
| Controller | HTTP handling, validation, response shaping, timing aggregation |
| Service | Business logic, orchestration, LLM calls |
| Repository | Data access, query building |

- Controllers NEVER access repositories directly
- Services NEVER handle HTTP concerns (request/response objects)
- Repositories NEVER contain business logic

## Performance Timing

Controllers SHOULD measure execution time using `performance.now()` and include timing data in responses:

```typescript
@Post()
async validate(@Body() dto: PromptContextDto): Promise<FullValidationResponse> {
  const totalStart = performance.now()
  const result = await this.service.process(dto.prompt, dto.context)

  return {
    ...result,
    timing: {
      ...result.timing,
      totalMs: Math.round(performance.now() - totalStart),
    },
  }
}
```

Services measure their own internal steps (LLM calls, curation steps) and return timing in the response DTO.

## DTOs & Validation

- Use `class-validator` + `class-transformer` for all request DTOs
- Separate request DTOs from response interfaces
- Request DTOs use `class-validator` decorators + `@ApiProperty()` for Swagger
- Response types are plain TypeScript interfaces (no class-validator needed)
- NEVER expose internal entities in API responses
- Check `@primer-guidy/nest-shared` for shared DTOs before creating new ones

## LLM Integration

- Inject LLM providers via `@Inject(TOKEN)` using tokens from `src/tokens.ts`
- NEVER import from `@anthropic-ai/sdk` or any provider SDK directly — use `@primer-guidy/llm-services`
- System prompts live in `src/prompts/` folder — NEVER inline in service files
- Use low temperature (0-0.3) for classification/validation, higher (0.7) for generation
- `LlmModule.register()` supports multiple providers per server with different tokens and model env vars

For full LLM patterns (port/adapter architecture, factory, error handling, type system), see `llm-integration.mdc`. For pipeline patterns (metrics, retries, concurrency, JSON validation, prompt management), see `llm-pipeline.mdc`.

## Server-to-Server Communication

For internal service calls (e.g., guardian-server calling brain), create a dedicated client service:

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class BrainClientService {
  private readonly baseUrl: string
  private readonly apiKey: string

  constructor() {
    this.baseUrl = process.env['BRAIN_BASE_URL'] ?? 'http://localhost:3011'
    this.apiKey = process.env['BRAIN_API_KEY'] ?? ''
  }

  async generate(prompt: string, context: string): Promise<GenerationResponseDto> {
    const response = await fetch(`${this.baseUrl}/api/generate`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'X-API-Key': this.apiKey,
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({ prompt, context }),
    })
    // ... error handling
  }
}
```

- Use `fetch` directly — no need for `@nestjs/axios` or HTTP module
- Always send `X-API-Key` header for authenticated endpoints
- Throw `HttpException` on errors with the upstream status code

## Docker

- ALL servers use the shared `docker/Dockerfile.server` (parameterized via `APP_NAME` and `APP_PORT` build args)
- NEVER create per-server Dockerfiles
- Server-to-server communication uses Docker network hostnames in local, Cloud Run URLs in production
- `docker-compose.yml` sets build context to monorepo root (`.`) with explicit `dockerfile` path

## Dev Scripts

```json
{
  "dev": "ts-node --swc -r reflect-metadata src/main.ts",
  "build": "nest build",
  "start": "node dist/main.js",
  "test": "vitest run",
  "test:watch": "vitest",
  "typecheck": "tsc --noEmit",
  "lint": "eslint src/"
}
```

- Use `ts-node --swc -r reflect-metadata` for local dev — NOT `tsx` (decorator issues)
- `nest build` uses SWC for production builds
- `vitest run` for tests (add `vitest` to devDependencies)
